# for co-occurence analyses all columns you want to test for associations need to be binary (1=presence / 0=absence) 

# co-occurrence analysis of common mhc STs and coronavirus
# we define common STs as all mhc STs that occur in at least 10 individuals 

# first select all columns with allele and virus info we want to investigate for co-occurrence 
cooccur_H.abae <-subset(H.abae, select=c("CoV.229E","CoV.2B","CoV.2Bbasal",
                                "ST1", "ST2", "ST3", "ST4", "ST7", "ST10", "ST11", "ST12"))             

# create a transposed matrix
cooccur_H.abae_long <- t(as.matrix(cooccur_H.abae))

# now apply the co-occurrence function
# just fyi when you look up the cooccurr package it shows co-occurrence of "species" and "sites",
# and these terms are also used within the function
# so here the "species" are alleles and pathogens and the "sites" are the individuals

H.abae_STs <- cooccur(mat = cooccur_H.abae_long, type = "spp_site", thresh = FALSE, spp_names = TRUE)

#### remove double ups ####
heatmap.dat<-subset(heatmap.dat, sp2_name!="CoV.2B")
heatmap.dat<-subset(heatmap.dat, sp2_name!="CoV.2Bbasal")

#### specify asterix assignment for
heatmap.dat.p_gt <- heatmap.dat %>% 
  mutate(Asterisks_gt = ifelse(p_gt  <= 0.001, "***",
                            ifelse(p_gt <= 0.01, "**",
                                   ifelse(p_gt  <= 0.05, "*", NA))))
heatmap.dat.p_lt <- heatmap.dat %>% 
  mutate(Asterisks_lt = ifelse(p_lt  <= 0.001, "***",

                                   ifelse(p_lt  <= 0.05, "*", NA))))

co-infection hypothesis

### load library specific to this section 
library("vcd")
## Loading required package: grid
bats$coinfection2 = as.factor(
  paste(bats$CoV.229E,bats$CoV.2B,bats$CoV.2Bbasal,sep="")
)
#levels(sample_data(bats)$coinfection2) 
levels(bats$coinfection2) = c("uninfected", "CoV2Bbasal", 
                              "CoV2B", "CoV2Bbasal+CoV2B", 
                              "CoV229E","CoV229E+CoV2Bbasal", 
                              "CoV229E+CoV2B", "CoV229E+CoV2B+CoV2Bbasal")

#### given the distinct, i.e. pleiotropic, effects observed in bats (Hip D) with 
#### ST12 (susceptible to 229E, resistant to CoV2B)
#### we can hypothesise that co-infection with 229E and CoV2B
#### should be particularly uncommon amongst individuals with e.g. ST12

#Hypothesis: fewer individuals with ST12 should be co-infected with CoV2B and 229E

### setting up table with relevant comparisons ###
con.table <- table(bats$ST12, bats$coinfection2)
ST12_only229E.2B<-con.table[,-c(2,4,6,8)]

assoc(ST12_only229E.2B, shade = TRUE, las=3)

#### this confirms that fewer individuals with ST12 are
#### a) uninfected, CoV2B infected or co-infected
#### but b) more individuals are singly infected with CoV229E

viral intensity hypothesis and Figure 3B

### load library specific to this section 
library(ggsignif)

####setting up labels
bats$ST12.labels <- factor(as.factor(bats$ST12), levels = c("0", "1"), 
                  labels = c("MHC ST12 absent", "MHC ST12 present"))


### we test in a subset of CoV229E infected individuals whether individuals with ST12 ...
### are more severely infected based on the CT-value
subset229E<-subset(bats, CoV.229E == 1 )

wilcox.test(X229Elike ~ ST12, data=subset229E) # data is non-normal
## 
##  Wilcoxon rank sum test with continuity correction
## 
## data:  X229Elike by ST12
## W = 4784, p-value = 0.01658
## alternative hypothesis: true location shift is not equal to 0
ggplot(data = subset229E, aes(as.factor(ST12), X229Elike, fill = as.factor(ST12)))+
  geom_boxplot()+geom_hline(yintercept=38.0, linetype="dashed")+geom_jitter(shape=21, size=3, width = .15)+theme_bw(base_size=16)+theme(legend.position = "none")+ylim(20,40)+scale_fill_manual(values=c("grey80", "grey50"))+ylab("CT-value of CoV-229E infected bats") +geom_signif(comparisons = list(c("0", "1")), map_signif_level=TRUE, textsize = 7) + xlab("")+scale_x_discrete(labels=c("0" = "ST12 absent", "1" = "ST12 present"))

fitness proxy body condition/mass and Figure 4

### we first calculate body condition from non-pregnant individuals
bats<-subset(bats, REP!="P" & REP!="PL") # removes pregnant females
bats<-subset(bats, Mass!="NA") # removes individuals without mass measurement
bats<-subset(bats, FA!="NA") # removes individuals without forearm length measurement

### we calculate body condition from mass divided by forearm length
bats$body.condition<-bats$Mass/bats$FA

### calculate residuals from regression between CoV229E and ST12
bats$resid_CoV229E<-resid(glm(CoV.229E~ST12, data=bats))
bats$resid_CoV2B<-resid(glm(CoV.2B~ST12, data=bats))

### initial model based on biologicallly sensible hypothesis that ...
### an interaction between ST12 and CoV229E/2B might be visible if 
### a) CoV infection reduced condition and ...
### b) ST12 increases/decreases resistance/susceptibility
lm1<-(lmer(log(body.condition) ~ as.factor(ST12) * resid_CoV229E + as.factor(ST12) * resid_CoV2B+ species + number_ST  + number_ST2 +(1|sample_period), data=bats, na.action=na.fail))
